In the civil law. A teacher;
one who has the care of youth; a tutor; a
guardian. Du Cange; Spelman.

A witness testifies on '"behalf' of the party who calls him, notwithstanding his evidence proves to be adverse
to that party's case. Richerson v. Sternburg, 65 Ill. 274. See, further, 12 Q. B. 693;
18 Q. B. 512.

An orgavized and systematic collection of rules of jurisprudence;
as, particularly, the body of the civil law, or
corpus juris civilis.

In old French law. An assemblage of houses surrounded with walls;
a fortified town or village.
In old English law. A borough, a village.
